<i>...and Roosevelt removed Wallace
from the Bureau of Economic Warfare...</i>

196
00:15:44,402 --> 00:15:48,157
<i>...and put Byrnes in charge
of the new office of war mobilization.</i>

197
00:15:49,532 --> 00:15:53,662
<i>But Wallace still had a powerful supporter,
the American working man.</i>

198
00:15:56,080 --> 00:16:00,256
<i>Today, few remember that the Second
World War saw more strikes...</i>

199
00:16:00,418 --> 00:16:04,264
<i>...by organized labor
than at any other time in U.S. history.</i>

200
00:16:04,422 --> 00:16:09,144
<i>In 1944 alone 1 million workers
were on strike at one time or another.</i>

201
00:16:09,302 --> 00:16:12,806
<i>The war had rejuvenated
American capitalism.</i>

202
00:16:13,014 --> 00:16:16,769
<i>Corporate profits rose
from $6.4 billion in 1940...</i>

203
00:16:16,934 --> 00:16:20,689
<i>...to $10.8 billion in 1944.</i>

204
00:16:20,855 --> 00:16:23,574
<i>Put simply, the war was good business.</i>

205
00:16:23,733 --> 00:16:28,284
<i>But in the face of rising corporate
profits, workers' wages were frozen.</i>

206
00:16:28,446 --> 00:16:32,076
<i>As a result,
a wave of strikes rocked the nation.</i>

207
00:16:33,826 --> 00:16:36,045
<i>Americans versus Americans...</i>

208
00:16:36,204 --> 00:16:38,798
<i>...a tragic spectacle in
these critical times...</i>

209
00:16:38,956 --> 00:16:43,507
<i>...when unity is essential
to the preservation of democracy.</i>

210
00:16:46,255 --> 00:16:50,226
<i>Detroit was the key city
in Roosevelt's Arsenal of Democracy.</i>

211
00:16:50,384 --> 00:16:53,103
<i>A great arsenal of democracy.</i>

212
00:16:53,262 --> 00:16:56,141
<i>Many African-American
families migrated north...</i>

213
00:16:56,599 --> 00:16:59,944
<i>...in search of work in
the armaments factories.</i>

214
00:17:01,771 --> 00:17:04,945
<i>Racial tensions soon escalated.</i>

215
00:17:05,107 --> 00:17:07,201
<i>One demonstrator jeered:</i>

216
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:09,488
<i>I'd rather see Hitler and Hirohito win...</i>

217
00:17:09,654 --> 00:17:11,827
<i>...than work beside a Nigger
on the assembly line.</i>

218
00:17:11,989 --> 00:17:14,242
<i>In June violence exploded...</i>

219
00:17:14,408 --> 00:17:18,458
<i>...exacerbated by the city's
nearly all-white police force.</i>

220
00:17:18,621 --> 00:17:23,172
<i>Federal troops arrived to restore order
with live ammunition.</i>

221
00:17:23,334 --> 00:17:28,215
<i>Thirty four were killed in the riots,
25 of them black.</i>

222
00:17:29,465 --> 00:17:34,141
<i>Wallace went to Detroit
to survey the damage. He was appalled.</i>

223
00:17:34,303 --> 00:17:40,276
We cannot fight
to crush Nazi brutality abroad...

224
00:17:40,434 --> 00:17:44,689
...and condone race riots at home.

225
00:17:44,855 --> 00:17:48,155
<i>Years later this remark
would be echoed by civil rights leader...</i>

226
00:17:48,317 --> 00:17:53,118
<i>...Martin Luther King
in reference to the Vietnam War.</i>

227
00:17:53,281 --> 00:17:59,288
<i>By 1944, powerful labor leaders
Sidney Hillman and Scotsman Phil Murray...</i>

228
00:17:59,453 --> 00:18:02,423
<i>...expressing complete confidence
in Wallace...</i>

229
00:18:02,582 --> 00:18:07,759
<i>...had taken a dislike to the new men like
Byrnes taking power in Washington.</i>

230
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:10,844
<i>But the Anti-Wallace forces
told the president...</i>

231
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:14,978
<i>...that a Wallace re-nomination
as vice president would split the party.</i>

232
00:18:15,136 --> 00:18:19,016
<i>The president would not answer
their ultimatum. He stalled for time.</i>

233
00:18:19,181 --> 00:18:23,607
<i>Eleanor Roosevelt reminded him that Wallace had
been there with him since the beginning...</i>

234
00:18:23,769 --> 00:18:25,817
<i>...a fellow visionary.</i>

235
00:18:25,980 --> 00:18:30,156
<i>But the president's attitude
towards Wallace remained a puzzle.</i>

236
00:18:31,277 --> 00:18:36,454
<i>He sent Wallace to evaluate
the war's forgotten front in China.</i>

237
00:18:36,616 --> 00:18:41,998
<i>U.S. any Jiang Jieshi had been
fighting Japan since the early 1930s...</i>

238
00:18:42,163 --> 00:18:46,634
<i>...and with his wife, the powerful
American-educated Madame Jiang...</i>

239
00:18:46,792 --> 00:18:49,386
<i>...had strong ties to the US conservatives.</i>

240
00:18:49,545 --> 00:18:54,176
<i>Wallace, however, saw the growing power
of Mao Tse-Tung's communist army...</i>

241
00:18:54,342 --> 00:18:57,892
<i>...and was unsure of Jiang's future.</i>

242
00:18:58,054 --> 00:19:03,481
<i>His final report was considered
too controversial and suppressed.</i>

243
00:19:04,560 --> 00:19:08,815
<i>On his return, Wallace was summoned
immediately to meet the president.</i>

244
00:19:08,981 --> 00:19:11,700
<i>The ticket would be
the subject of discussion.</i>

245
00:19:11,859 --> 00:19:14,032
<i>It was the moment
Wallace had been dreading.</i>

246
00:19:14,195 --> 00:19:17,620
His affection for me
seemed to be completely undimmed...

247
00:19:17,782 --> 00:19:21,912
...because I can remember him
pulling me down...

248
00:19:22,078 --> 00:19:26,879
...so his mouth was next to my ear
and saying:

249
00:19:27,083 --> 00:19:30,758
"Henry, I hope it will
be the same old team."

250
00:19:34,799 --> 00:19:38,178
<i>When the convention opened,
he was waiting for that support.</i>

251
00:19:38,761 --> 00:19:43,437
<i>But increasingly iii, the president
staying in San Diego, only sent a note.</i>

252
00:19:43,599 --> 00:19:50,574
Franklin Delano Roosevelt said,
"If I were a delegate to this convention...

253
00:19:50,731 --> 00:19:53,575
<i>...I would vote for Henry A. Wallace."</i>

254
00:19:53,734 --> 00:19:56,783
<i>Despite these words,
it was a cruel blow.</i>

255
00:19:56,946 --> 00:20:00,621
<i>The president was not willing
to fight for his vice president.</i>

256
00:20:00,825 --> 00:20:02,953
<i>But Wallace remained the favorite.</i>

257
00:20:03,119 --> 00:20:07,124
<i>Labor told the president that the strike-
breaking Jimmy Byrnes was not acceptable.</i>

258
00:20:07,289 --> 00:20:08,461
<i>He was out.</i>

259
00:20:08,624 --> 00:20:13,095
<i>Desperate, the bosses
led by Edwin Pauley, Robert Hannegan...</i>

260
00:20:13,254 --> 00:20:18,385
...Ed <i>Flynn, Ed Kelly and others
needed an 11th-hour substitute.</i>

261
00:20:18,551 --> 00:20:21,555
<i>And they settled on Missouri Senator
Harry Truman...</i>

262
00:20:21,721 --> 00:20:26,693
<i>...a man of limited qualifications,
but one with few enemies.</i>

263
00:20:26,851 --> 00:20:32,358
<i>A graduate of high school, he'd been
involved in three failed businesses.</i>

264
00:20:32,523 --> 00:20:34,901
<i>He'd served honorably in World War I.</i>

265
00:20:35,067 --> 00:20:41,245
<i>His most ambitious business venture,
a haberdashery, went belly up in 1922.</i>

266
00:20:41,407 --> 00:20:42,784
<i>And in 1933, he wrote:</i>

267
00:20:42,950 --> 00:20:44,623
<i>Tomorrow I'll be 49...</i>

268
00:20:44,785 --> 00:20:48,881
<i>...but for all the good I have done,
the 40 might as well be left off.</i>

269
00:20:49,039 --> 00:20:52,839
<i>A year later, Kansas City
political boss Tom Pendergast...</i>

270
00:20:53,002 --> 00:20:56,552
<i>...after having been turned down
by his first four choices...</i>

271
00:20:56,714 --> 00:21:00,059
<i>...picked the 50-year-old Truman
to run for the senate.</i>

272
00:21:00,217 --> 00:21:02,686
<i>When asked why, Pendergast replied:</i>

273
00:21:02,845 --> 00:21:04,438
<i>I wanted to demonstrate...</i>

274
00:21:04,597 --> 00:21:08,477
<i>...that a well-oiled machine could send
an office boy to the senate.</i>

275
00:21:08,642 --> 00:21:10,315
<i>Shunned by most senators...</i>

276
00:21:10,478 --> 00:21:13,197
<i>...who dismissed him
as the Senator from Pendergast...</i>

277
00:21:13,355 --> 00:21:18,031
<i>...and failing to gain Roosevelt's
endorsement in his re-election bid...</i>

278
00:21:18,194 --> 00:21:22,495
<i>...Truman worked hard to achieve
respectability in his second senate term.</i>

279
00:21:22,656 --> 00:21:24,533
<i>But a Gallup poll on the opening day...</i>

280
00:21:24,700 --> 00:21:28,876
<i>...showed 65 percent supporting Wallace
as vice president...</i>

281
00:21:29,038 --> 00:21:34,090
<i>...Jimmy Byrnes had 3 percent of the vote,
and Truman came in eighth with 2 percent.</i>

282
00:21:34,251 --> 00:21:39,382
<i>As Wallace arrived at the convention labor
leaders Hillman and Murray had delivered.</i>

283
00:21:39,548 --> 00:21:41,721
<i>Wallace supporters were there
by the thousands.</i>

284
00:21:41,884 --> 00:21:45,639
<i>Murray, in a thick Scottish accent,
shouted to his men:</i>

285
00:21:45,805 --> 00:21:48,399
<i>"Wallace! That's it! Just keep pounding!"</i>

286
00:21:48,557 --> 00:21:53,654
The future must bring equal wages
for equal work...

287
00:21:53,813 --> 00:21:56,862
...regardless of sex or race.

288
00:21:58,400 --> 00:22:01,995
<i>Wallace's speech
was interrupted constantly by applause.</i>

289
00:22:02,154 --> 00:22:05,158
<i>A chant of, "We Want Wallace,"
filled the hall.</i>

290
00:22:05,324 --> 00:22:08,919
We want Wallace! We want Wallace!
We want Wallace!

291
00:22:09,078 --> 00:22:11,297
<i>Someone hijacked the loudspeakers...</i>

292
00:22:11,455 --> 00:22:14,584
<i>...and played Wallace's campaign song
with its chorus:</i>

293
00:22:14,750 --> 00:22:17,720
<i>"Iowa, Iowa,
that's where the tall corn grows."</i>

294
00:22:17,878 --> 00:22:21,348
<i>Iowa...
That's where the tall corn grows...</i>

295
00:22:21,507 --> 00:22:26,263
<i>Furious, Ed Pauley threatened
to cut the sound to the amplifiers.</i>

296
00:22:26,428 --> 00:22:31,309
<i>A victorious vote was almost a foregone
conclusion, a Wallace victory was certain.</i>

297
00:22:31,475 --> 00:22:36,572
<i>Florida Senator Pepper realized if he got
Wallace's name in nomination this night...</i>

298
00:22:36,730 --> 00:22:38,482
<i>...Wallace would sweep the convention.</i>

299
00:22:38,649 --> 00:22:41,448
<i>He fought his way through the crowd
to get to the microphone.</i>

300
00:22:41,610 --> 00:22:46,662
<i>But the bosses were now demanding
that Session Chair Samuel Jackson adjourn.</i>

301
00:22:46,824 --> 00:22:50,124
<i>This chaos was a fire hazard,
they screamed.</i>

302
00:22:50,286 --> 00:22:53,790
<i>Not knowing what to do,
Jackson called the vote for adjournment.</i>

303
00:22:53,956 --> 00:22:57,677
<i>A few said aye,
but the overwhelming majority boomed nay.</i>

304
00:22:57,835 --> 00:23:03,387
<i>And yet, Jackson had the gall to announce
that the vote to adjourn had passed.</i>

305
00:23:03,549 --> 00:23:06,428
<i>It was outrageous.
Confusion filled the hall.</i>

306
00:23:06,594 --> 00:23:10,224
<i>Pepper had reached the first step
of the stage, only five feet...</i>

307
00:23:10,389 --> 00:23:12,517
<i>...probably nine seconds
from the microphone...</i>

308
00:23:12,683 --> 00:23:16,813
<i>...before the bosses forced adjournment
against the win of the delegates.</i>

309
00:23:16,979 --> 00:23:19,778
<i>If he could have nominated Wallace
in those moments...</i>

310
00:23:19,940 --> 00:23:25,788
<i>...there's no doubt Henry Wallace would've been
overwhelmingly returned as vice president.</i>

311
00:23:25,946 --> 00:23:30,042
<i>"What I understood," Pepper wrote,
"was that for better or worse...</i>

312
00:23:30,200 --> 00:23:33,704
<i>...history was turned topsy-turvy
that night in Chicago."</i>

313
00:23:33,871 --> 00:23:36,215
<i>Samuel Jackson apologized to Pepper
the next day...</i>

314
00:23:36,373 --> 00:23:40,094
<i>...and Pepper wrote in his autobiography
that Jackson said;</i>

315
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:42,254
<i>"I had strict instructions from Hannegan...</i>

316
00:23:42,421 --> 00:23:45,925
<i>...not to let the convention nominate
the vice-president last night."</i>

317
00:23:46,091 --> 00:23:49,595
<i>Hillman and Murray rallied the same troops
to return the next day...</i>

318
00:23:49,762 --> 00:23:52,231
<i>...and see it through to victory.</i>

319
00:23:53,140 --> 00:23:59,364
<i>But over that night, Edwin Pauley and the anti-
Wallace forces united behind Harry Truman.</i>

320
00:23:59,521 --> 00:24:01,364
<i>Deals were cut. Positions offered.</i>

321
00:24:01,523 --> 00:24:06,324
<i>Ambassadorships,
postmaster positions. Cash payoffs.</i>

322
00:24:06,487 --> 00:24:08,535
<i>Bosses called every state chairman...</i>

323
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:12,702
<i>...telling them that Roosevelt wanted
the Missouri senator as his running mate.</i>

324
00:24:12,868 --> 00:24:17,089
<i>Bob Hannegan managed to put up
16 favorite son nominees...</i>

325
00:24:17,247 --> 00:24:19,716
<i>...to draw votes away from Wallace...</i>

326
00:24:19,875 --> 00:24:22,719
<i>...and then channeled those votes
to Truman.</i>

327
00:24:22,878 --> 00:24:29,227
<i>Even so, the next day when voting began,
